					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">American lawyer, politician, and judge</div>
<p class="mw-empty-elt">

</p>
<table class="infobox vcard"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-above" style="font-size: 100%;"><div class="fn" style="font-size:125%;">Leon Parker Miller</div></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-image"><span class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Frameless"><a href="/wiki/File:Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="Black and white photograph portrait of a man in a suit, white dress shirt, and necktie." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/38/Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg/220px-Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="305" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/38/Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg/330px-Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/38/Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg/440px-Leon_P._Miller_Portrait_1954.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2976" data-file-height="4128" /></a></span><div class="infobox-caption" style="line-height:normal;padding-top:0.2em;">Portrait of Miller, published in the <i>St. Paul Recorder</i>, 1954</div></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data"></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background:lavender;line-height:normal;padding:0.2em;">Judge of the Criminal Court of <a href="/wiki/McDowell_County,_West_Virginia" title="McDowell County, West Virginia">McDowell County, West Virginia</a><sup id="cite_ref-fn1_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn1-2">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="border-bottom:none"><span class="nowrap"><b>In office</b></span><br />1968–1968</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Preceded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">L. R. Morgan</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Succeeded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Harry G. Camper</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="border-bottom:none"><span class="nowrap"><b>In office</b></span><br />1968–1972</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Preceded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Harry G. Camper</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Succeeded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Rudolph J. Murensky</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background:lavender;line-height:normal;padding:0.2em;"><a href="/wiki/District_Court_of_the_Virgin_Islands" title="District Court of the Virgin Islands">United States Attorney for the District of the Virgin Islands</a></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="border-bottom:none"><span class="nowrap"><b>In office</b></span><br />1954–1962</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left">President</th><td class="infobox-data"><a href="/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" title="Dwight D. Eisenhower">Dwight D. Eisenhower</a><br /><a href="/wiki/John_F._Kennedy" title="John F. Kennedy">John F. Kennedy</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Preceded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Cyril Michael</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Succeeded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Almeric L. Christian</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background:lavender;line-height:normal;padding:0.2em;">Member of the City Council of <a href="/wiki/Welch,_West_Virginia" title="Welch, West Virginia">Welch, West Virginia</a></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="border-bottom:none"><span class="nowrap"><b>In office</b></span><br />1944–1948</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Preceded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">William Gannaway</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Succeeded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Joseph G. Travis</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background:lavender;line-height:normal;padding:0.2em;">Assistant <a href="/wiki/District_attorney" title="District attorney">Prosecuting Attorney</a> for <a href="/wiki/McDowell_County,_West_Virginia" title="McDowell County, West Virginia">McDowell County, West Virginia</a></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="border-bottom:none"><span class="nowrap"><b>In office</b></span><br />1928–1936</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="text-align:left"><span class="nowrap">Succeeded by</span></th><td class="infobox-data">Joseph G. Travis</td></tr><tr style="display:none"><td colspan="2">
</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background:lavender">Personal details</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Born</th><td class="infobox-data"><span style="display:none">(<span class="bday">1899-04-27</span>)</span>April 27, 1899<br /><a href="/wiki/Knoxville,_Tennessee" title="Knoxville, Tennessee">Knoxville, Tennessee</a>, U.S.</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Died</th><td class="infobox-data">February 4, 1980<span style="display:none">(1980-02-04)</span> (aged&#160;80)<br /><a href="/wiki/Welch,_West_Virginia" title="Welch, West Virginia">Welch, West Virginia</a>, U.S.</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Resting place</th><td class="infobox-data label">Restlawn Memorial Gardens, <a href="/wiki/Bluefield,_West_Virginia" title="Bluefield, West Virginia">Bluefield, West Virginia</a>, U.S.</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Political party</th><td class="infobox-data"><a href="/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title="Republican Party (United States)">Republican</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Spouse</th><td class="infobox-data">Mildred Elizabeth Foster Miller</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Children</th><td class="infobox-data">3</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><a href="/wiki/Alma_mater" title="Alma mater">Alma mater</a></th><td class="infobox-data"><a href="/wiki/North_Carolina_A%26T_State_University" title="North Carolina A&amp;T State University">North Carolina A&amp;T State College</a><br /><a href="/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania_Law_School" title="University of Pennsylvania Law School">University of Pennsylvania Law School</a> (<a href="/wiki/Bachelor_of_Laws" title="Bachelor of Laws">LL.B.</a>)</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Profession</th><td class="infobox-data">Lawyer, politician, and judge</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-below" style="border-top: 1px solid right;"><div></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Leon Parker Miller</b> (April 27, 1899 – February 4, 1980) was an American lawyer, politician, and judge, in the <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">U.S. state</a> of <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia" title="West Virginia">West Virginia</a>. Miller served as <a href="/wiki/District_Court_of_the_Virgin_Islands" title="District Court of the Virgin Islands">U.S. Attorney for the District of the Virgin Islands</a> from 1954 to 1962. He was appointed the first African-American judge in West Virginia in April 1968, and became the state's first elected African-American judge in November 1968.
</p><p>Born in <a href="/wiki/Knoxville,_Tennessee" title="Knoxville, Tennessee">Knoxville, Tennessee</a>, in 1899, Miller was raised in <a href="/wiki/Roanoke,_Virginia" title="Roanoke, Virginia">Roanoke, Virginia</a>. He attended <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina_A%26T_State_University" title="North Carolina A&amp;T State University">North Carolina A&amp;T State College</a>, and in 1922, he graduated from <a href="/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania_Law_School" title="University of Pennsylvania Law School">University of Pennsylvania Law School</a> with a <a href="/wiki/Bachelor_of_Laws" title="Bachelor of Laws">Bachelor of Laws</a>. Miller commenced his career in law in <a href="/wiki/Williamson,_West_Virginia" title="Williamson, West Virginia">Williamson, West Virginia</a>, in 1922, and in 1924, he relocated to <a href="/wiki/Welch,_West_Virginia" title="Welch, West Virginia">Welch, West Virginia</a>, and established a law firm with former <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia_House_of_Delegates" title="West Virginia House of Delegates">West Virginia House of Delegates</a> member <a href="/wiki/Harry_J._Capehart" title="Harry J. Capehart">Harry J. Capehart</a> and <a href="/wiki/Recorder_of_deeds#District_of_Columbia" title="Recorder of deeds">Recorder of Deeds for the District of Columbia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Arthur_G._Froe" title="Arthur G. Froe">Arthur G. Froe</a>. He served as assistant <a href="/wiki/District_attorney" title="District attorney">prosecuting attorney</a> for <a href="/wiki/McDowell_County,_West_Virginia" title="McDowell County, West Virginia">McDowell County</a> from 1928 to 1936, and as a member of the Welch <a href="/wiki/Municipal_council" title="Municipal council">city council</a> from 1944 to 1948.
</p><p>Miller was appointed by President <a href="/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" title="Dwight D. Eisenhower">Dwight D. Eisenhower</a> as the United States Attorney for the District of the Virgin Islands in 1954, and he was reappointed to the position in 1958. He served as U.S. attorney until 1962, and then returned to his law practice in Welch. In 1968, he was elected as a write-in candidate as judge of the criminal court,<sup id="cite_ref-fn1_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn1-2">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> becoming the first elected African-American judge in West Virginia, and the first Republican elected to major office in McDowell County since the 1930s. He retired from the bench in 1972 and continued the practice of law until his death in Welch in 1980.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_life_and_education">Early life and education</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Early life and education"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Leon Parker Miller was born on April 27, 1899, in <a href="/wiki/Knoxville,_Tennessee" title="Knoxville, Tennessee">Knoxville, Tennessee</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> He had three sisters: Georgia, Eunice, and Grace.<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Miller was raised in <a href="/wiki/Roanoke,_Virginia" title="Roanoke, Virginia">Roanoke, Virginia</a>, where he attended school.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The first job Miller held as a child was of a <a href="/wiki/Shoeshiner" title="Shoeshiner">shoeshiner</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> He began attending college at the age of 14, and paid his tuition by working as a waiter and <a href="/wiki/Bellhop" title="Bellhop">bellhop</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Miller attended <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina_A%26T_State_University" title="North Carolina A&amp;T State University">North Carolina A&amp;T State College</a> in <a href="/wiki/Greensboro,_North_Carolina" title="Greensboro, North Carolina">Greensboro, North Carolina</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> While attending North Carolina A&amp;T, Miller was a member of the college's Mechanic Arts Society, and he delivered an oration at the society's anniversary exercises in May 1918.<sup id="cite_ref-Greensboro_Daily_News_1_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Greensboro_Daily_News_1-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> He then attended the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania_Law_School" title="University of Pennsylvania Law School">University of Pennsylvania Law School</a>, where he received a <a href="/wiki/Bachelor_of_Laws" title="Bachelor of Laws">Bachelor of Laws</a> degree in 1922.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-UP_1922_62_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UP_1922_62-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_law_and_political_careers">Early law and political careers</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Early law and political careers"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="Black and white photograph view of buildings in downtown Welch, West Virginia, in 1915." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg/220px-Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="135" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg/330px-Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg/440px-Downtown_Welch_WV_1915.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2661" data-file-height="1630" /></a><figcaption>Downtown <a href="/wiki/Welch,_West_Virginia" title="Welch, West Virginia">Welch</a>, 1915</figcaption></figure>
<p>Miller commenced his career in law in 1922 in <a href="/wiki/Williamson,_West_Virginia" title="Williamson, West Virginia">Williamson, West Virginia</a>, where he remained for two years.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> In 1924, he relocated to <a href="/wiki/Welch,_West_Virginia" title="Welch, West Virginia">Welch, West Virginia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Miller became a law partner of former <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia_House_of_Delegates" title="West Virginia House of Delegates">West Virginia House of Delegates</a> member <a href="/wiki/Harry_J._Capehart" title="Harry J. Capehart">Harry J. Capehart</a> and <a href="/wiki/Recorder_of_deeds#District_of_Columbia" title="Recorder of deeds">Recorder of Deeds for the District of Columbia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Arthur_G._Froe" title="Arthur G. Froe">Arthur G. Froe</a>, and they had a successful law practice together known as Froe, Capehart, and Miller.<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Harris_1927_179_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harris_1927_179-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Smith_1993_241_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Smith_1993_241-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Following the death of Froe in 1932, he and Capehart continued their practice under the name of Capehart and Miller.<sup id="cite_ref-The_McDowell_Times_2_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_McDowell_Times_2-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> From 1928 to 1936, Miller served as an assistant <a href="/wiki/District_attorney" title="District attorney">prosecuting attorney</a> for <a href="/wiki/McDowell_County,_West_Virginia" title="McDowell County, West Virginia">McDowell County</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_7_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_7-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> He had been appointed to the position following a recommendation from county prosecuting attorney, Wilson Anderson.<sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_4_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_4-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> According to the <i><a href="/wiki/Charleston_Daily_Mail" title="Charleston Daily Mail">Charleston Daily Mail</a></i> in 1932, Miller was believed to be the only African-American assistant prosecuting attorney in the state.<sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_4_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_4-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> He resigned from the position effective June 1, 1936, to return to private practice, and he was succeeded by African-American attorney Joseph G. Travis.<sup id="cite_ref-The_McDowell_Times_2_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_McDowell_Times_2-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_7_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_7-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_10_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_10-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> In 1934, Miller campaigned for the Republican nomination for a seat on the McDowell County board of education,<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_3_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_3-14">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> and in August of that year, he was elected as the Republican candidate for the board.<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_4_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_4-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> In October 1934, Miller was named chairman of the McDowell County Colored Republican Organization advisory committee.<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_9_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_9-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> He also served as a member of the Welch <a href="/wiki/Municipal_council" title="Municipal council">city council</a> from 1944 to 1948.<sup id="cite_ref-fn2_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn2-22">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Miller was a contributor to various periodicals to include <i><a href="/wiki/The_Crisis" title="The Crisis">The Crisis</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Opportunity:_A_Journal_of_Negro_Life" title="Opportunity: A Journal of Negro Life">Opportunity: A Journal of Negro Life</a></i>. In his 1935 article, "The Negro and the 'Closed Shop'", Miller wrote about African-American <a href="/wiki/Strikebreaker" title="Strikebreaker">strikebreakers</a> and the descrimination against African-American workers by <a href="/wiki/Organized_labor" class="mw-redirect" title="Organized labor">organized labor</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Miller_1935_168–170,_189_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Miller_1935_168–170,_189-23">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> In his 1936 article, "A Greater N.A.A.C.P.", Miller discussed the need for the <a href="/wiki/NAACP" title="NAACP">NAACP</a> to play an expanded, centralized role in organizing and improving the lives of African-Americans.<sup id="cite_ref-Miller_1936_213–214_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Miller_1936_213–214-24">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> In March 1941, Miller was a guest speaker on the <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBS</a> national radio program, <i><a href="/wiki/Wings_Over_Jordan_Choir" title="Wings Over Jordan Choir">Wings Over Jordan</a></i>, in commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the North Carolina A&amp;T State College.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Independent-Herald_1_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Independent-Herald_1-25">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 1938, Miller was the president of the McDowell County branch of the NAACP, in which capacity, he and the county NAACP sought to retain the African-American <a href="/wiki/Civilian_Conservation_Corps" title="Civilian Conservation Corps">Civilian Conservation Corps</a> camp in the county's Big Creek district.<sup id="cite_ref-The_McDowell_Times_1_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_McDowell_Times_1-26">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Miller also later served on the West Virginia Bar Association legal ethics committee for <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia%27s_5th_congressional_district" title="West Virginia&#39;s 5th congressional district">West Virginia's 5th congressional district</a> in 1947.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Leader_1_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Leader_1-27">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> Miller served as the assistant committee chairperson for arrangements for the <a href="/wiki/1948_Republican_National_Convention" title="1948 Republican National Convention">1948 Republican National Convention</a> in Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1-28">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> In addition, he was an alternate delegate representing the 5th congressional district at the <a href="/wiki/1952_Republican_National_Convention" title="1952 Republican National Convention">1952 Republican National Convention</a> in Chicago.<sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1-28">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_2_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_2-29">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_5_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_5-30">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="United_States_attorney">United States attorney</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: United States attorney"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In 1954, President <a href="/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" title="Dwight D. Eisenhower">Dwight D. Eisenhower</a> appointed Miller to a four-year term as the <a href="/wiki/District_Court_of_the_Virgin_Islands" title="District Court of the Virgin Islands">United States Attorney for the District of the Virgin Islands</a> to replace Cyril Michael.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Miller's appointment was referred to the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Senate_Committee_on_the_Judiciary" title="United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary">United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary</a> on November 8, 1954, his appointment was reported by the committee on December 1, and he was confirmed by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Senate" title="United States Senate">U.S. Senate</a> on December 2.<sup id="cite_ref-Bailey_1955_328_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bailey_1955_328-32">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_3_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_3-33">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_3_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_3-34">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> When Miller arrived on <a href="/wiki/Saint_Thomas,_U.S._Virgin_Islands" title="Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands">Saint Thomas</a>, Virgin Islands District Court Judge Herman E. Moore had not yet been notified of Miller's appointment.<sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Miller was sworn in following the judge's receipt of a <a href="/wiki/Telegram" class="mw-redirect" title="Telegram">telegram</a> confirming Miller's appointment.<sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> During his tenure, Miller was involved with the <a href="/wiki/Codification_(law)" title="Codification (law)">codification</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Virgin_Islands" title="United States Virgin Islands">U.S. Virgin Islands</a>' laws.<sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Eisenhower reappointed Miller to another four-year term as U.S. attorney in 1958, and he was confirmed by the U.S. Senate on August 22, 1958.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_2_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_2-35">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_4_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_4-36">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> In 1961, at the end of Miller's term, the position of the <a href="/wiki/Attorney_General_of_the_United_States_Virgin_Islands" title="Attorney General of the United States Virgin Islands">Attorney General of the United States Virgin Islands</a> was created, which relieved the office of the U.S. Attorney from trying all cases within the territorial boundaries of the U.S. Virgin Islands.<sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> In total, Miller held that post for eight years until 1962.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_215_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_215-37">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> President <a href="/wiki/John_F._Kennedy" title="John F. Kennedy">John F. Kennedy</a> appointed Almeric L. Christian to succeed Miller.<sup id="cite_ref-OUSA_1989_176_31-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OUSA_1989_176-31">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Judicial_and_later_law_career">Judicial and later law career</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Judicial and later law career"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Following his tenure as a U.S. attorney, Miller returned to Welch and resumed the practice of law.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In August 1962, Miller addressed approximately 2,200 delegates of the state's Republican convention at the <a href="/wiki/Charleston_Coliseum_%26_Convention_Center" title="Charleston Coliseum &amp; Convention Center">Charleston Civic Center</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1_28-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_1-28">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Weirton_Daily_Times_1_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Weirton_Daily_Times_1-38">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Weirton_Daily_Times_2_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Weirton_Daily_Times_2-39">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> Miller's speech was praised by columnists in the <i><a href="/wiki/The_Register-Herald" title="The Register-Herald">Beckley Post-Herald</a></i> and the <i>Charleston Daily Mail</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_6_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_6-40">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> In his speech, he noted that while he believed the Republican Party had something to offer all groups, he warned the party against making separate appeals to different groups and to prejudices.<sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_6_40-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_6-40">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="Large, stone courthouse atop a hill" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg/220px-McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg/330px-McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg/440px-McDowell_County_Courthouse.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="768" /></a><figcaption><a href="/wiki/McDowell_County_Courthouse_(West_Virginia)" title="McDowell County Courthouse (West Virginia)">McDowell County Courthouse</a>, Welch</figcaption></figure>
<p>In March 1968, McDowell County Criminal Court judge L. R. Morgan died, causing a vacancy on the bench.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_6_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_6-41">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_5_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_5-42">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> On April 9, 1968, Miller was elected and appointed by the McDowell County Bar Association to serve as special judge of the criminal court for the April term until Governor <a href="/wiki/Hulett_C._Smith" title="Hulett C. Smith">Hulett C. Smith</a> appointed Morgan's successor.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_6_41-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_6-41">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Charleston_Daily_Mail_5_42-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Charleston_Daily_Mail_5-42">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> Governor Smith subsequently appointed Harry G. Camper to replace Morgan until a permanent replacement for the remainder of Morgan's term could be elected in the <a href="/wiki/1968_United_States_elections" title="1968 United States elections">1968 election</a> in November 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-Myers_1968_282_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Myers_1968_282-43">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> Neither the <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia_Democratic_Party" title="West Virginia Democratic Party">Democratic</a> or Republican parties held primary elections for nominees to the seat, and therefore, neither party entered a candidate for the November ballot.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> A write-in campaign was then organized for Miller and Beediah Hassan, and stickers for both candidates were disseminated to voters on the day of the election—November 5, 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Miller was subsequently elected judge of the McDowell County Criminal Court in the 1968 election.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Miller initially received a total of 1,317 write-in votes and 1,197 "sticker votes".<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-fn3_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn3-45">&#91;c&#93;</a></sup> His election was certified in November, and on December 12, 1968, Governor Smith proclaimed Miller as the duly elected judge of the criminal court, with a total of 2,526 votes.<sup id="cite_ref-Myers_1969_596_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Myers_1969_596-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Charleston_Gazette_1_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Charleston_Gazette_1-47">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> Miller became the first African-American judge elected in West Virginia.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-WVAH_1_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WVAH_1-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> He also became the first Republican elected to a major office in McDowell County since the 1930s.<sup id="cite_ref-WVAH_1_48-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WVAH_1-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>
Miller viewed his election as both a step forward for African-American West Virginians and as a tribute to McDowell County.<sup id="cite_ref-WVAH_1_48-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WVAH_1-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> Regarding his election, he stated:<sup id="cite_ref-WVAH_1_48-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WVAH_1-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> </p><blockquote class="templatequote"><p>I think it's helpful to the younger people of the state to know that they have an opportunity, if they strive hard enough, to achieve things that a few years ago that were unthinkable. I've been here in the county about 44 years now, and it's a very gratifying thing for me to know that my neighbors, friends, and people of this community have sufficient confidence in me to elect me to this very important position.</p></blockquote>
<p>On November 18, 1968, Miller sat for his first hearing, in which he ordered a psychiatric examination of a 17-year old arrested on felonious assault charges, the results of which were to be used as part of his bond hearing.<sup id="cite_ref-WVAH_1_48-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WVAH_1-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_2_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_2-49">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1971, an act of the <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia_Legislature" title="West Virginia Legislature">West Virginia Legislature</a> changed the name of the Criminal Court of McDowell County to the Intermediate Court of McDowell County.<sup id="cite_ref-Myers_1971_380_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Myers_1971_380-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Miller fulfilled the remainder of Morgan's six-year term, which ended on December 31, 1972.<sup id="cite_ref-Myers_1969_358,_676_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Myers_1969_358,_676-50">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Myers_1970_356,_696_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Myers_1970_356,_696-51">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup> In November 1972, he announced he would not run for reelection, and he retired from the bench at the end of his term in December.<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_2_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_2-52">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> Following his retirement, Miller took a six-month vacation in the U.S. Virgin Islands, where he formerly served as U.S. attorney.<sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_2_52-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_2-52">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> Miller was succeeded on the bench of the intermediate court by Democrat Rudolph J. Murensky.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Carson_1973_380_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Carson_1973_380-53">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>While reflecting on his tenure on the bench, Miller remarked that he was sometimes criticized for being too lenient.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> He explained, "But when I see a young man who has stolen something on a lark when he was half drunk, I can't help thinking that there are men in Charleston who have stolen millions and are walking around free."<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Miller further stated that he preferred <a href="/wiki/Probation" title="Probation">probation</a> for offenders in most cases, with the exception of when the crime is serious enough or if the criminal is a <a href="/wiki/Recidivism" title="Recidivism">repeat offender</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_4_5-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_4-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Personal_life">Personal life</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Personal life"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Miller married Mildred Elizabeth Foster of Greensboro, North Carolina.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> While in Welch, he and his family resided on Court Street.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Miller and his wife had three daughters: Artrelle Miller Wheatley, who worked for the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Foundation" title="Ford Foundation">Ford Foundation</a>; Jane Miller Johnson, a psychiatric social worker at <a href="/wiki/Presbyterian_Hospital_(New_York_City)" title="Presbyterian Hospital (New York City)">Presbyterian Hospital</a>; and Lydia Patricia Miller Adams, a physical therapist who operated the U.S. Virgin Islands' disabled children's division.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Miller and his wife had five grandchildren.<sup id="cite_ref-Welch_Daily_News_1_3-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Welch_Daily_News_1-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Miller was an active speaker and leader in the community, and he regularly delivered addresses at events. In November 1932, Miller and <a href="/wiki/Memphis_Tennessee_Garrison" title="Memphis Tennessee Garrison">Memphis Tennessee Garrison</a> were speakers at an event in <a href="/wiki/Bluestone,_West_Virginia" title="Bluestone, West Virginia">Bluestone</a> on the importance of voting in the upcoming <a href="/wiki/1932_United_States_elections" title="1932 United States elections">1932 elections</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_5_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_5-54">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> In May 1933, he gave the main address for the graduation commencement ceremony at Northfork Colored High School in <a href="/wiki/Northfork,_West_Virginia" title="Northfork, West Virginia">Northfork</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_8_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_8-55">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> In February 1936, Miller delivered an address on "Race Planning" at <a href="/wiki/Bluefield_State_College" class="mw-redirect" title="Bluefield State College">Bluefield State College</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bluefield,_West_Virginia" title="Bluefield, West Virginia">Bluefield</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_6_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_6-56">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> In May 1949, Miller delivered the main address at the Conley High School graduation in <a href="/wiki/Mullens,_West_Virginia" title="Mullens, West Virginia">Mullens</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Beckley_Post-Herald_1_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Beckley_Post-Herald_1-57">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_3_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_3-58">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_5_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_5-59">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> In March 1969, he gave a presentation on "Law and Order" at <a href="/wiki/Mullens_High_School" title="Mullens High School">Mullens High School</a> in which he stated, "Our greatest asset is our young people."<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_1_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_1-60">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup> He further told the students, "The youth of today are courageous, determined, and admirable."<sup id="cite_ref-The_Raleigh_Register_1_60-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Raleigh_Register_1-60">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup> In addition, Miller was a member of the <a href="/wiki/Alpha_Phi_Alpha" title="Alpha Phi Alpha">Alpha Phi Alpha</a> fraternity.<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Hinton_Daily_News_2_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hinton_Daily_News_2-61">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Later_life_and_death">Later life and death</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Later life and death"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Following a long illness, Miller was declared dead on arrival at a hospital in Welch on February 4, 1980.<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_1_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bluefield_Daily_Telegraph_1-62">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> At his funeral service, Miller's successor on the intermediate court bench, Rudolph Murensky, remarked of Miller, "He was one of the most outstanding lawyers to ever practice in this area. No one had greater compassion."<sup id="cite_ref-Young_1980_72_4-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Young_1980_72-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_works">Selected works</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Leon_P._Miller&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Selected works"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul><li><cite class="citation journal cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/sim_opportunity-a-journal-of-negro-life_1935-06_13_6/">"The Negro and the 'Closed Shop'<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span>"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Opportunity:_A_Journal_of_Negro_Life" title="Opportunity: A Journal of Negro Life">Opportunity: A Journal of Negro Life</a></i>. <b>XIII</b> (6). New York City, New York: <a href="/wiki/National_Urban_League" title="National Urban League">National Urban League</a>: 168–170, 189. June 1935.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Opportunity%3A+A+Journal+of+Negro+Life&amp;rft.atitle=The+Negro+and+the+%27Closed+Shop%27&amp;rft.volume=XIII&amp;rft.issue=6&amp;rft.pages=168-170%2C+189&amp;rft.date=1935-06&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fsim_opportunity-a-journal-of-negro-life_1935-06_13_6%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALeon+P.+Miller" class="Z3988"></span></li>
<li><cite class="citation journal cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/sim_crisis_1936-07_43_7/">"A Greater N.A.A.C.P."</a> <i><a href="/wiki/The_Crisis" title="The Crisis">The Crisis</a></i>. <b>43</b> (7). New York City, New York: Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.: 213–214 July 1936.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Crisis&amp;rft.atitle=A+Greater+N.A.A.C.P.&amp;rft.volume=43&amp;rft.issue=7&amp;rft.pages=213-214&amp;rft.date=1936-07&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fsim_crisis_1936-07_43_7%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALeon+P.+Miller" class="Z3988"></span></li></ul>
